PROMPT START

You are turning the following blog into a simple, skimmable, high-impact email written specifically for franchisors.

Your goal is to extract the 5 biggest insights and rewrite them in ultra-simple layman’s terms, so a franchisor can read the email in seconds and understand exactly why it matters.

AUDIENCE

Franchisors, multi-brand operators, and founders who want to:

Protect their system

Reduce liability

Strengthen insurance requirements

Protect franchisee investments

Scale without surprises

They skim everything.
Your writing must be instantly understandable.

NON-NEGOTIABLE RULES
1. No jargon — ever

Write like you’re explaining to someone outside the insurance world.

2. No acronyms on first mention

For ANY coverage or insurance term:

A) Write out the full coverage name the FIRST time
B) After first mention, you MAY use the acronym

No exceptions.

3. Define each coverage ONCE at the bottom of the email

One sentence

Ultra-simple

5th–6th grade reading level

Never repeat definitions

Only define coverages used in the email

Definitions do NOT count toward bullet word limits

EMAIL STRUCTURE & RULES
1. Subject Line (must be a hook)

Requirements:

2–6 words

Curiosity-based

Emotionally compelling

Clear tension or stakes

Relevant to franchisor risk & system protection

Follow Neil Patel best practices (short, punchy, intriguing)

Examples to mimic (do not reuse):

“Your Hidden Risk”

“The Gap That Hurts”

“A Costly Blind Spot”

“Before This Breaks You”

“What Most Brands Miss”

2. Intro (2 sentences MAX)

Follow StoryBrand:

Sentence 1: Identify the single core problem addressed in the blog.

Sentence 2: State why this matters to protecting the brand or franchisees.

3. Top 5 Takeaways (MUST be bulleted)

Produce exactly five takeaways using standard bullet points:

• or – ONLY.

Rules:

One idea per bullet

Under 14 words (definitions don’t count)

Ultra-simple, high-level

Must read like quick-hit headlines

No definitions inside the bullets

If a coverage is mentioned for the first time in a bullet, write out the full name

After that first mention, you may use the acronym in later bullets

Format example (structure only):

Top 5 takeaways:
• [Short, simple insight #1]
• [Short, simple insight #2]
• [Short, simple insight #3]
• [Short, simple insight #4]
• [Short, simple insight #5]

4. Definitions Section (end of email)

Include ONLY IF coverages were mentioned.

Title it:

Definitions (in simple terms):

Then list each coverage once like this:

General Liability Insurance: coverage that protects the business if someone gets hurt or property is damaged.
Employment Practices Liability Insurance: coverage that protects the business from things like discrimination, sexual harassment, or wrongful termination.
(etc.)

One sentence each.
No jargon.
No acronyms here.

5. Closing CTA

Use this EXACT text:

If you want the full breakdown so you can protect your brand and your franchisees, you can read the full article here: [Insert Link]

FINAL OUTPUT FORMAT

Return the finished email like this:

Subject: [High-hook subject line]

Hi there,

[2-sentence intro]

Top 5 takeaways:
• [Bullet #1]
• [Bullet #2]
• [Bullet #3]
• [Bullet #4]
• [Bullet #5]

If you want the full breakdown so you can protect your brand and your franchisees, you can read the full article here: [Insert Link]

Definitions (in simple terms):
[Only include definitions for coverages used in the email. One sentence each.]

Now rewrite the blog below following ALL rules above:
[PASTE BLOG HERE]

PROMPT END
